==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: handfast
<hw>hand"fast`</hw> <pr>(h⟦acr⟧nd"f⟦adot⟧st`)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>Hold; grasp</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Custody; power of confining or keeping.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A contract; specifically, an espousal.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>handfast</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: handfast
<hw>hand"fast`</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Fast by contract; betrothed by
joining hands.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Bale.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>handfast</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: handfast
<hw>hand"fast`</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>handfasted</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>handfasting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To pledge; to
bind.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To betroth by joining hands, in order to permit
cohabitation, before the formal celebration of marriage; in some parts
of Scotland it was in effect to marry provisionally, permitting
cohabitation for a year, after which the marriage could be formalized or
dissolved.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ Handfasting was a simple contract of agreement under
which cohabitation was permitted for a year, at the end of which time
the contract could be either dissolved or made permanent by a formal
marriage. Such marriages, at first probably not intended to be
temporary, are supposed to have originated in Scotland from a scarcity
of clergy, and to have existed at times in other countries.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>Century Dict. 1906.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>handfast</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: handfast
<hw>hand"fast`</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[G. <ets>handfest</ets>;
